docs.abstract: How will President Trump’s protectionism go over at the elite World Economic Forum meeting in Davos, Switzerland, which draws leaders who believe in globalism and free trade?
docs.snippet: How will President Trump’s protectionism go over at the elite World Economic Forum meeting in Davos, Switzerland, which draws leaders who believe in globalism and free trade?
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — As the annual meeting of the World Economic Forum gets underway here this week, the conversation among business and policy leaders in the Alps is already dominated by one topic: What will the first-time invitee President Trump say?

headline.main: Fox in the Globalist Henhouse? Davos Awaits Trump’s Arrival

docs.abstract: The trade-off we make for free online content, social sharing and convenience is the willful relinquishing of our privacy. It’s part of the deal.
docs.snippet: The trade-off we make for free online content, social sharing and convenience is the willful relinquishing of our privacy. It’s part of the deal.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook’s co-founder, begins two days of testimony on Capitol Hill, where he will undoubtedly face withering criticism over his site’s handling of user data, millions of people will spend the day the way they always do: scrolling through their News Feeds, sending each other messages and “liking” posts, oblivious to any privacy concerns.

headline.main: Failed by Facebook, We’ll Return to the Scene of the Crime. We Always Do.
headline.print_headline: Our Privacy Has Eroded. We’re O.K. With That.

docs.abstract: James Rosen, a Washington correspondent, left Fox News last month, and Joel Achenbach, a Washington Post reporter, received a 90-day suspension on Wednesday.
docs.snippet: James Rosen, a Washington correspondent, left Fox News last month, and Joel Achenbach, a Washington Post reporter, received a 90-day suspension on Wednesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two prominent journalists, one at Fox News and one at The Washington Post, are facing allegations of inappropriate workplace conduct.

headline.main: 2 Journalists, at Fox and Washington Post, Are Accused of Misconduct
headline.print_headline: 2 Journalists, at Fox and Washington Post, Are Accused of Misconduct

docs.abstract: Mr. Draghi’s critique of comments by the U.S. Treasury secretary came as the eurozone central bank tried to quash speculation about an early end to its economic stimulus program.
docs.snippet: Mr. Draghi’s critique of comments by the U.S. Treasury secretary came as the eurozone central bank tried to quash speculation about an early end to its economic stimulus program.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — Mario Draghi, the president of the European Central Bank, directed unusually sharp criticism at Steven Mnuchin, the United States Treasury secretary, on Thursday, effectively accusing Mr. Mnuchin of violating agreements among nations against starting currency wars.

headline.main: Draghi, Chief of Europe’s Central Bank, Chides Mnuchin Over Dollar Comments
headline.print_headline: E.C.B. Chief Draghi Chides U.S. Treasury Secretary Over Dollar Drop

docs.abstract: Friday’s session ended the S.&P. 500’s worst week in two years, and followed slumping sessions in global markets in Europe and Asia.
docs.snippet: Friday’s session ended the S.&P. 500’s worst week in two years, and followed slumping sessions in global markets in Europe and Asia.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks on Wall Street closed lower on Friday, ending the worst week for the Standard & Poor’s 500-stock index in two years, as investors weighed a brewing trade war between China and the United States that could hobble an otherwise healthy global economy.

headline.main: Wall St. Closes Lower, as a U.S.-China Trade War Looms
headline.print_headline: Wall St. Closes Lower, as a U.S.-China Trade War Looms

byline.original: By Jack Ewing and Alexandra Stevenson

docs.abstract: Indications of slowing growth are not yet strong enough to cause the European Central Bank to revise its timetable for winding down economic stimulus.
docs.snippet: Indications of slowing growth are not yet strong enough to cause the European Central Bank to revise its timetable for winding down economic stimulus.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — The eurozone economy has been a puzzle lately. Some indicators are pointing up, some down and some sideways. It’s hard to know whether growth is losing momentum or just pausing for breath.

headline.main: With Eurozone Economy Wavering, E.C.B. Leaves Policy Unchanged
headline.print_headline: Europe Bank Sticks to Plan To Phase Out Its Stimulus

docs.abstract: Daimler suspended a manager and BMW said an employee had been “relieved of his current tasks” amid an outcry over emissions experiments on monkeys.
docs.snippet: Daimler suspended a manager and BMW said an employee had been “relieved of his current tasks” amid an outcry over emissions experiments on monkeys.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — The German carmakers BMW and Daimler said on Wednesday that they had taken action against executives involved in an organization that sponsored emissions experiments on monkeys, as the companies tried to squelch a public outcry that threatens to tarnish the image of Germany’s most important exports.

headline.main: BMW and Daimler Move Against Executives Over Diesel Tests on Monkeys
headline.print_headline: Car Executives Punished Over Tests on Monkeys

docs.abstract: Herbert Diess was not tarred by Volkswagen’s emissions scandal, but must navigate a company culture known for being insular and hard to change.
docs.snippet: Herbert Diess was not tarred by Volkswagen’s emissions scandal, but must navigate a company culture known for being insular and hard to change.
docs.lead_paragraph: WOLFSBURG, Germany — Herbert Diess has one big advantage as he takes over as the chief executive of Volkswagen after his official appointment Thursday. He is not a product of Wolfsburg, the carmaker’s base.

headline.main: Volkswagen’s New C.E.O. Is an Outsider. That’s an Asset, and a Liability.
headline.print_headline: Volkswagen’s New Leader Is an Outsider. That’s an Asset, and a Liability.

docs.abstract: The authorities searched the Stuttgart offices of the sports car maker, one of Volkswagen’s most profitable units, and said a Porsche board member was a suspect in an emissions-cheating scandal.
docs.snippet: The authorities searched the Stuttgart offices of the sports car maker, one of Volkswagen’s most profitable units, and said a Porsche board member was a suspect in an emissions-cheating scandal.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — A top executive at Volkswagen’s Porsche unit was among those targeted when dozens of police officers raided the sports car maker’s headquarters on Wednesday as part of an investigation into emissions cheating, German prosecutors said.

headline.main: Top Porsche Official Targeted in German Police Raid Tied to Diesel Scheme
headline.print_headline: Porsche Board Member Among Targets as Police Raid Offices in Emissions Scandal

docs.abstract: European officials expressed disappointment that an exemption to steel and aluminum tariffs was not permanent, leaving the global economy in limbo.
docs.snippet: European officials expressed disappointment that an exemption to steel and aluminum tariffs was not permanent, leaving the global economy in limbo.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — American allies did not bother to conceal their annoyance Tuesday with the Trump administration’s last-minute decision to delay punitive aluminum and steel tariffs by a month, in their view leaving a sword of Damocles hanging over the global economy.

headline.main: Europe Is Annoyed, Not Grateful, After Trump Delays Tariffs
headline.print_headline: Why Europe Isn’t Grateful For Reprieve From Tariffs
